<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n15036d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n15" href="#n15036d">N15 (VI.D.2)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n15all.htm#n15036d"> 36(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> (Brother Robert) / Tristansaga</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">In Norway, from at least 1225 or so, these romances had come into vogue under the patronage of King H&aacute;kon, at whose instance some, if not most, of the existing translations were made. He is expressly named as having commissioned <mark>the sagas of Tristram</mark>, translated in 1236 by &lsquo;<mark>Brother Robert</mark>,&rsquo; of Elis and Bosamunda by the same hand, of Ivent (= Yvain) and of the mantle (<i>M&ouml;ttula saga</i>), as well as a translation of the <i>lais</i> of Marie of France. <small> W. A. Craige, <a name="ICEL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ICEL"><cite title="source">The Icelandic Sagas</cite></a>, (1913) 99-100</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c15212d" href="c15all.htm#c15212d">VI.C.15:212(d)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
